---
// when to see a doctor — CONTEXT page (deferred from Phase 5), safety-forward. NOT a graded remedy:
// it's the boundary of the site — the sleep problems a supplement can't fix and a clinician should
// see. No tier badge, no evidence-gate chips. Red-flag symptoms are framed as signs clinicians
// screen for (guidance directing to care, not efficacy claims). The one evidentiary specific — that
// even chronic-insomnia drug options are only weakly recommended, so diagnosis matters more than a
// pill — is cited to the 2017 AASM guideline, verified firsthand.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const redFlags = [
  {
    sign: 'loud snoring with pauses in breathing',
    detail:
      'if a bed partner notices you stop breathing, gasp, or choke in your sleep (especially with heavy daytime sleepiness), that points toward obstructive sleep apnoea. No supplement treats it, and untreated it carries real health risks. Ask about a sleep study.',
  },
  {
    sign: 'insomnia most nights, for months',
    detail:
      "clinicians generally call insomnia “chronic” when it runs at least three nights a week for three months or more. At that point it's a condition to treat properly, not to keep papering over with nightly supplements.",
  },
  {
    sign: 'crawling, restless legs at night',
    detail:
      'an urge to move your legs with uncomfortable sensations, worse in the evening and relieved by movement, can be restless legs syndrome, sometimes linked to low iron. It has specific treatments a clinician can pursue.',
  },
  {
    sign: 'falling asleep suddenly in the day',
    detail:
      'overwhelming daytime sleep attacks, or sudden muscle weakness with strong emotion, warrant evaluation for narcolepsy or another sleep disorder, not self-treatment.',
  },
  {
    sign: 'acting out dreams',
    detail:
      'shouting, punching, or otherwise physically acting out dreams during sleep can be REM sleep behaviour disorder, which needs medical assessment (both for injury risk and what it can signal).',
  },
  {
    sign: 'sleep loss with low mood or anxiety',
    detail:
      "when poor sleep travels with persistent low mood, anxiety, or (urgently) any thoughts of self-harm, the sleep is a symptom. Treat the whole picture with a clinician; seek help immediately for thoughts of self-harm.",
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="when to see a doctor about sleep: the limits of a supplement | Somnary"
  description="supplements are for mild, occasional sleeplessness. loud snoring with breathing pauses, months of insomnia, restless legs, acting out dreams, or sleep loss with low mood are signs to see a clinician, not to self-treat."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/when-to-see-a-doctor"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · when to get professional help</p>
      <h1 class="title">when to see a doctor<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Somnary grades remedies for mild, occasional sleeplessness. It doesn't diagnose, and some
        sleep problems need a clinician rather than anything on a shelf. This page is about
        recognising those: the honest edge of what a supplement can do.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="this isn't a remedy and isn't graded. it's the boundary of the site: the point where the right move is a professional, not a purchase."
    />

    <!-- top callout: supplements have limits (caution) -->
    <section class="callout sev-caution" role="note" aria-label="when to seek care">
      <div class="callout-head">
        <span class="sigil" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
        <p class="callout-title">supplements are for mild, short-term sleeplessness</p>
      </div>
      <p class="callout-body">
        If your sleep problem is severe, persistent, or comes with any of the signs below, that's a
        reason to see a clinician, not to keep trying supplements. A remedy that masks a treatable
        disorder can delay the care that would actually fix it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- section 01: red flags -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">signs to get evaluated</h2>
      <div class="flags">
        {
          redFlags.map((f) => (
            <div class="flag">
              <p class="flag-sign">{f.sign}</p>
              <p class="flag-detail">{f.detail}</p>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 02: why a pill can mask the problem -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">why reaching for a pill can be the wrong first move</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Even for straightforward chronic insomnia, the medication options aren't a slam dunk: the
          American Academy of Sleep Medicine's own guideline gives every one of them only a
          <strong>weak recommendation</strong>.<Fn n={1} /> That's a strong hint that the answer isn't
          usually &ldquo;find the right pill&rdquo;: it's getting the diagnosis right. For chronic
          insomnia specifically, the recommended first-line treatment is a structured behavioural
          programme (CBT-I), not a supplement or a sedative. A clinician can tell whether that's what
          you need, or whether something like apnoea is the real driver.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 03: prepare for the visit -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what to bring to the appointment</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <ul>
          <li>
            a rough <strong>sleep diary</strong> (bed and wake times, how long to fall asleep, night
            wakings) for a week or two.
          </li>
          <li>
            a full list of <strong>everything you take</strong>, including supplements, melatonin, and
            anything bought over the counter.
          </li>
          <li>
            what a <strong>bed partner has noticed</strong>: snoring, breathing pauses, leg
            movements, acting out dreams.
          </li>
          <li>caffeine, alcohol, and screen habits in the hours before bed.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 04: urgent -->
    <section class="section" id="urgent">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">when it's urgent</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Some situations shouldn't wait for a routine appointment. If you or someone else has
          <strong>thoughts of self-harm</strong>, reach a crisis line now: in Australia,
          <strong>Lifeline on 13 11 14</strong>; in the US, <strong>call or text 988</strong>. If
          someone is <strong>unrousable, struggling to breathe, or has taken a dangerous amount</strong>
          of any substance, call your local emergency number (<strong>000</strong> in Australia,
          <strong>911</strong> in the US). For a suspected poisoning, the
          <strong>Poisons Information Centre is 13 11 26</strong> in Australia and
          <strong>Poison Help is 1-800-222-1222</strong> in the US; elsewhere, contact your local
          poisons service or emergency number.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={[
      {
        n: 1,
        cite: 'Sateia MJ, Buysse DJ, Krystal AD, et al. Clinical Practice Guideline for the Pharmacologic Treatment of Chronic Insomnia in Adults (AASM). J Clin Sleep Med. 2017;13(2):307–349.',
        finding:
          'across the drugs assessed for chronic insomnia, every recommendation the guideline issues is graded weak — the evidence for pharmacologic treatment is modest, which underlines getting a proper diagnosis over self-treating with a pill.',
        pmid: '27998379',
        doi: '10.5664/jcsm.6470',
      },
    ]} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: 1180px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--sp-8) var(--sp-7) var(--sp-9);
  }
  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-label);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .dot {
    color: var(--primary);
  }
  .head {
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-6);
  }
  .title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    line-height: var(--lh-3xl);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: var(--sp-3) 0 var(--sp-5);
  }
  .dek {
    font-size: var(--text-md);
    line-height: var(--lh-md);
    color: var(--muted);
    max-width: 68ch;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* caution callout — §2.12 caution register (grade-c) */
  .callout {
    border-radius: var(--r-lg);
    border: 1px solid;
    padding: var(--sp-6);
    margin-top: var(--sp-7);
  }
  .sev-caution {
    background: var(--grade-c-tint);
    border-color: var(--grade-c);
  }
  .callout-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--sp-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-4);
  }
  .sigil {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 26px;
    height: 26px;
    flex: none;
    border-radius: var(--r-pill);
    background: var(--grade-c);
    color: var(--surface);
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    line-height: 1;
  }
  .callout-title {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-label);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--grade-c);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .callout-body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--lh-base);
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .section {
    border-top: var(--border-hairline);
    padding-top: var(--sp-6);
    margin-top: var(--sp-8);
  }
  .section-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    line-height: var(--lh-xl);
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: var(--sp-2) 0 var(--sp-5);
  }

  /* red-flag rows */
  .flags {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    border: var(--border-hairline);
    border-radius: var(--r-lg);
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .flag {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;
